04736nam a22006015i 9780822390770DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223907707 a10.1515/97808223907702doi  a(DE-B1597)554514  a(OCoLC)631201995  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aJN2594.2 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aAbélès, Marc, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Politics of Survival /cMarc Abélès; Benjamin Lee, Jane Kramer, Dilip Parameshwar Gaonkar. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPublic planet books00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTranslator's Note -- tPreface to the English Edition -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 The End of the Brilliance That the Future Will Bring -- t2 Globalization and the State: A False Debate? -- t3 Virtual Europe, a Space of Uncertainty -- t4 Understanding the Displacement of Politics: From Convivance to Survival -- t5 A Necessary Detour -- t6 From Power to Humanity -- t7 The Economy of Survival -- t8 Toward Global Politics -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this provocative analysis of global politics, the anthropologist Marc Abélès argues that the meaning and aims of political action have radically changed in the era of globalization. As dangers such as terrorism and global warming have moved to the fore of global consciousness, foreboding has replaced the belief that tomorrow will be better than today. Survival, outlasting the uncertainties and threats of a precarious future, has supplanted harmonious coexistence as the primary goal of politics. Abélès contends that this political reorientation has changed our priorities and modes of political action, and generated new debates and initiatives. The proliferation of supranational and transnational organizations-from the European Union to the World Trade Organization (WTO) to Oxfam-is the visible effect of this radical transformation in our relationship to the political realm. Areas of governance as diverse as the economy, the environment, and human rights have been partially taken over by such agencies. Non-governmental organizations in particular have become linked with the mindset of risk and uncertainty; they both reflect and help produce the politics of survival.Abélès examines the new global politics, which assumes many forms and is enacted by diverse figures with varied sympathies: the officials at meetings of the WTO and the demonstrators outside them, celebrity activists, and online contributors to international charities. He makes an impassioned case that our accounts of globalization need to reckon with the preoccupations and affiliations now driving global politics. The Politics of Survival was first published in France in 2006. This English-language edition has been revised and includes a new preface.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aPolitical psychology. 0aPoliticianszFrancexAttitudes. 0aPublic opinionzFrance. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aGaonkar, Dilip Parameshwar, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKleinman, Julie1 aKramer, Jane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLee, Benjamin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822390770zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822390770423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822390770.jpg  a978